nput: s = \"9080701\"\nOutput: false\nExplanation: There is no valid way to split s.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= s.length <= 20\ns only consists of digits.\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def splitString(self, s: str) -> bool:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def splitString(self, s: str) -> bool:\n        \n        def can_split(index, prev_num, parts_count):\n            # If we reached the end of the string and have more than one part, return True\n            if index == len(s):\n                return parts_count > 1\n            \n            for i in range(index, len(s)):\n                # Get the current number from the substring\n                current_num = int(s[index:i+1])\n                \n                # Check if it's the first part or if it's one less than the previous part\n                if parts_count == 0 or current_num == prev_num - 1:\n                    # Recursively check the rest of the string\n                    if can_split(i + 1, current_num, parts_count + 1):\n                        return True\n            \n            return False\n        \n        return can_split(0, -1, 0)\n```\n\nThis solution uses a recursive helper function `can_split` to explore all possible ways to split the string `s` into substrings that meet the criteria. The function tries to split the string starting from each position and checks if the resulting numerical values form a descending sequence where each value is one less than the previous one. The base case for the recursion is when the end of the string is reached, and more than one part has been formed.", "estimated_date": 1619913600000}